Introduction

  • Prevalence: 13% in women
  • Mortality rate: 2.6%
  • Symptoms: little to no before it is widespread
  • 4 Tumor types: Vary in location, size, shape and severity

Cancer.org, “Key Statistics for Breast Cancer” (2022). https://www.cancer.org/cancer/breast-cancer/about/how-common-is-breast-cancer.html

Aim

In this project we will investigate whether it is possible to detect and correctly classify the 4 breast cancer subtypes using different sets of protein expression data and compare the results of the classification.

Materials and Methods

Mertins, P., Mani, D., Ruggles, K. et al. Proteogenomics connects somatic mutations to signalling in breast cancer. Nature 534, 55–62 (2016). https://doi.org/10.1038/nature18003

Results - Common proteins after GLM

  • Still found 1000 more significant proteins in each subtype after glm()
  • ggvenn()
  • Only 24 significant protein IDs common for all the 4 subtypes

Results - Common proteins after GLM

  • Downregulated: Basal-like and HER2-enriched.
  • Upregulated: Luminal-A and Luminal-B
  • Similar protein expression levels between each patient within heat maps

Results - Common Protein BC Data

  • The first 17 PCs were chosen for clustering
  • Cluster distributions are not similar to subtype distributions
  • Accuracy of plot: 16.9%

Results - Full BC data

  • Number of PCs reduced from 77 to 65
  • No clear patterns
  • Little of the variance is explained by PC1 and PC2
  • Accuracy of plot: 36.4%

Results - Protein IDs common between PAM50 data and BC data

  • Number of PCs reduced from 26 to 15
  • 1st PC explains a much higher variance (34.9% compared to 10.7%)
  • Accuracy of this exact plot: 48.1%

Discussion

  • Best performer: PAM50
    • Only 26 out of 100 protein IDs used
  • Only considering the common genes instead of e.g. the unique genes
  • Improvements
    • Cluster Luminal-A and Luminal-B together
  • Reproducible method
